		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2008 SI"></a><br><code>sle2008s/paper03</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2008 SI</a> paper:</span><br><i>Grammar Recovery from Parse Trees and Metrics-Guided Grammar Refactoring</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/NicholasAKraft.html">Nicholas A. Kraft</a>, <a href="../profile/EdwardDuffy.html">Edward Duffy</a>, <a href="../profile/BrianAMalloy.html">Brian A. Malloy</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1109/TSE.2009.65">10.1109/TSE.2009.65</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The work recovers and refactors a language grammar from an existing hard-coded parser and analyses the recovered grammar using grammar metrics.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Its methodology addresses recovery of an unavailable language artefact (the grammar) from existing implementations, which is an upwards vertical transformation.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Context-free grammars are the central meta-language artefact being reconstructed and manipulated.
</li></ul></li></ul>
